✅ 1. What is systemd
systemd = init system + service manager in Linux
PID 1 process → controls boot process and services
Main responsibilities:

Service management
Boot process
Logging (journald)
Device & socket management
Target-based grouping (like runlevels)


✅ 2. Unit Types (important for interview)
.service → service
.socket → socket activation
.target → grouping of units
.mount → mount points
.timer → scheduled jobs (cron alternative)
.path → trigger based on file changes
.swap → swap partitions
.device → hardware devices

✅ 3. Basic systemctl Commands (MOST IMPORTANT)
Start a service
systemctl start nginx
Stop a service
systemctl stop nginx
Restart
systemctl restart nginx
Reload (no stop/start)
systemctl reload nginx
Enable (start at boot)
systemctl enable nginx
Disable
systemctl disable nginx
Check status
systemctl status nginx
Check if active
systemctl is-active nginx
Check if enabled
systemctl is-enabled nginx

✅ 4. Listing & Info Commands
List all services
systemctl list-units --type=service
List all active
systemctl list-units
List all (including inactive)
systemctl list-units --all
List failed services
systemctl --failed
Show unit details
systemctl show nginx

✅ 5. Targets (Runlevels Replacement)
Old → New
Runlevel 0 → poweroff.target
Runlevel 1 → rescue.target
Runlevel 3 → multi-user.target
Runlevel 5 → graphical.target
Runlevel 6 → reboot.target
Check default target
systemctl get-default
Set default target
systemctl set-default multi-user.target
Switch target immediately
systemctl isolate multi-user.target

✅ 6. Enable/Disable Boot Behavior
Enable service at boot
systemctl enable httpd
Disable
systemctl disable httpd
Mask service (completely block it)
systemctl mask httpd
Unmask
systemctl unmask httpd

✅ 7. Service Unit File Location
System services
/usr/lib/systemd/system/
Custom services (recommended)
/etc/systemd/system/
Runtime services
/run/systemd/system/

✅ 8. Service File Structure (VERY IMPORTANT)
Example breakdown:
[Unit]
Description=My App
After=network.target
[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/usr/bin/python app.py
Restart=always
[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

✅ Meaning of Each Field
[Unit] section
Description → service description
After → dependency (start after this)
Requires → hard dependency
[Service] section
ExecStart → main command
ExecStop → stop command
Restart → auto restart
Type → simple | forking | oneshot
[Install] section
WantedBy → which target wants this service

✅ 9. Important Daemon Commands
Reload systemd config (after editing file)
systemctl daemon-reload
Re-exec systemd
systemctl daemon-reexec

✅ 10. Logs (journalctl)
View all logs
journalctl
Service logs
journalctl -u nginx
Live logs
journalctl -f
Boot logs
journalctl -b
Previous boot
journalctl -b -1

✅ 11. Troubleshooting (DevOps Practical)
Check failed services
systemctl --failed
Check logs
journalctl -xe
Detailed service logs
journalctl -u service_name
Restart and check
systemctl restart service_name

✅ 12. Dependency Management
See dependencies
systemctl list-dependencies nginx
Reverse dependencies
systemctl list-dependencies --reverse nginx

✅ 13. Timer (Cron Alternative)
List timers
systemctl list-timers
Start timer
systemctl start backup.timer

✅ 14. System Power Commands
Shutdown
systemctl poweroff
Reboot
systemctl reboot
Suspend
systemctl suspend

✅ 15. Common DevOps Scenarios
Service not starting:
systemctl status nginx
journalctl -u nginx
Service auto restart:
Restart=always in service file
Run script as service:
Create .service file → add ExecStart → enable

✅ 16. Quick Interview One-Liners
systemctl = control systemd services
daemon-reload = reload unit files
target = group of services (runlevel replacement)
journalctl = logging system

